{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"e3d28b2e-36a5-46fb-9a1c-c15237d0a52f","content":"Yes, both are known MSTest v4 breaking changes. Here's what's happening:\n\n## 1. Lost test history in Azure DevOps\n\nMSTest v4 changed the **test-ID algorithm** (now based on the fully-qualified method name + stable hashing). Azure DevOps sees new IDs → new tests. There's no automatic migration; history is tied to the old IDs.\n\n## 2. `TestContext.TestName` in `[ClassInitialize]`\n\nIn v4, the `TestContext` passed to `[ClassInitialize]` is a **class-level context** — it's no longer associated with any specific test. Accessing `TestName` (or `TestResultsDirectory` in some cases) throws `InvalidOperationException`.\n\nYour fix for `SetupTests.cs` — don't rely on `TestName` at class-init time:\n\n```csharp\n[ClassInitialize]\npublic static void ClassInit(TestContext context)\n{\n    // context.TestName is unavailable here in v4\n    // Use context for class-scoped logging only\n}\n```\n\n## Other v4 changes to watch for\n\n| Area | Change |\n|------|--------|\n| **Parallel execution** | Now **method-level parallel by default**. Add `[assembly: Parallelize(Scope = ExecutionScope.ClassLevel)]` to restore v3 behavior. |\n| **`[AssemblyInitialize]`/`[AssemblyCleanup]`** | The containing class must also have `[TestClass]`. |\n| **`[ExpectedException]`** | Deprecated; use `Assert.ThrowsExactly<T>()` / `Assert.ThrowsExactlyAsync<T>()`. |\n| **`DataRow` display names** | Generated differently — may break test filters/selectors in CI. |\n| **`TestContext.Properties`** | Read-only in some lifecycle phases. |\n| **Timeout defaults** | `[Timeout]` now applies to the test method only, not setup/cleanup. |\n\nThe parallel-by-default change is the most common source of \"tests pass locally but fail in CI\" after upgrading.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"b9d06213-d86a-484f-9827-8257c395aa99","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking about known MSTest v4 breaking changes. Let me provide a comprehensive answer based on what I know about MSTest v4 changes.\n\nKey MSTest v4 breaking changes:\n\n1. **Test ID generation changed** — MSTest v4 changed how test IDs are computed (fully qualified names now include namespace). This causes Azure DevOps to treat all tests as new, losing history.\n\n2. **TestContext in ClassInitialize** — In v4, `TestContext` passed to `[ClassInitialize]` is no longer associated with a specific test. Accessing `TestContext.TestName` throws `InvalidOperationException` because at class-init time there's no \"current test.\" This is a deliberate change — the context is now a class-level context, not a test-level one.\n\n\n3. There are several other notable changes: `DeploymentItem` attributes behave differently, `DataRow` display names have changed, parallel execution runs by default at the method level now, `AssemblyInitialize` and `AssemblyCleanup` methods require their containing class to be marked with `[TestClass]`, `TestContext.Properties` can't be modified in certain scenarios, and the `ExpectedException` attribute is no longer recommended in favor of using `Assert.ThrowsException`.","outputTokens":829,"requestId":"4810:275D06:657DAFF:6DE7A9A:69FC010F"},"id":"c3211a59-e78f-42a6-813e-7ed70765e2a0","timestamp":"2026-05-07T03:04:01.053Z","parentId":"c62f6eeb-4945-4c5e-a083-49d763628db6"}
